	  <section id="fs-id1537170" class="conceptual-questions" type="conceptual-questions">
    <title>Conceptual Questions</title>
    <exercise id="fs-id2839906" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id1324803">
    <para id="import-auto-id1574074">What is the relationship between the accuracy and uncertainty of a measurement?</para>
    </problem></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id953198" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id1523627">
    <para id="import-auto-id1549505">Prescriptions for vision correction are given in units called <emphasis effect="italics"><emphasis effect="italics">diopters</emphasis></emphasis> (D). Determine the meaning of that unit. Obtain information (perhaps by calling an optometrist or performing an internet search) on the minimum uncertainty with which corrections in diopters are determined and the accuracy with which corrective lenses can be produced. Discuss the sources of uncertainties in both the prescription and accuracy in the manufacture of lenses.</para>
</problem></exercise>
</section>
    <section xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="fs-id1570825" type="problems-exercises" class="problems-exercises"><title>Problems &amp; Exercises</title><para id="import-auto-id1958096"><emphasis>Express your answers to problems in this section to the correct number of significant figures and proper units.</emphasis>    </para>
    <exercise id="fs-id2131067" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1511754">
    <para id="import-auto-id2589301">Suppose that your bathroom scale reads your mass as 65 kg with a 3% uncertainty. What is the uncertainty in your mass (in kilograms)?</para></problem>
    <solution id="fs-id888279">
    <para id="import-auto-id2596708">2 kg</para>
    </solution></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id1246911" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1347190">
    <para id="import-auto-id3205346">A good-quality measuring tape can be off by 0.50 cm over a distance of 20 m. What is its percent uncertainty?</para>
    </problem></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id2773103" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2765366">
    <para id="import-auto-id1532973">(a) A car speedometer has a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>5.0</m:mn><m:mtext>%</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{5.0%} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> uncertainty. What is the range of possible speeds when it reads <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>90</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>km/h</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"90"" km/h"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>? (b) Convert this range to miles per hour. <m:math><m:semantics><m:mfenced open="(" close=")"><m:mrow><m:mtext>1 km</m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext>0.6214 mi</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mfenced><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"1 km" "=" "0.6214 mi"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para></problem>
    <solution id="fs-id923761">
